div.p:
As a natural Consequence of the Heat of Enthusiasm by which (you are pleased to say) he was so evidently acted, in a following Paragraph, p. S. You say, In the next Place, we look upon Mr. Whitefield as an uncharitable, censorious and slanderous Man; 

   viz.
habitually such, for that is the Idea your Words seem to convey. But Gentlemen, does it follow that Peter could properly be stiled a cursing swearing Man, because with Oaths and Curses he denied his Lord? Or David, that Man after God's own Heart, be properly stiled a murdering adulterous Man, because he committed Adultery with Bathsheba, and murder'd her Husband Uriah? Or, can a Believer be stiled properly an Hypocrite, because he has yet got a great deal of Hypocrisy remaining in his Heart? I suppose by no Means. No more according to my Apprehensions can any Man be justly called an uncharitable, censorious and slanderous Man, if he be not habitually so, supposing it should be proved either from his Writings or Conduct, that he may have been somewhat rash or uncharitable in his Judgment passed upon some particular Persons or Things.
